| Notes                   = 
* Although {{WP|Jon Favreau}} did not return to direct ''Iron Man 3'', he still appears as [[Harold Hogan (Earth-199999)|Happy Hogan]] and retains his role as executive producer.
* {{WP|Wang Xueqi}} was initially reported to be playing a character named [[Radioactive Man|Chen Lu]], better known in the comics as the supervillain Radioactive Man.
* The film was under the working title, ''Caged Heat''. This name has also been used as a distribution alias for the ''Iron Man 3'' digital content packages. The working title of Iron Man 3 was later referenced in the ''[[Marvel One-Shot: All Hail the King]]'', when it was used as the name given to a TV series in which [[Trevor Slattery (Earth-199999)|Trevor Slattery]] played the main role of its rejected pilot.
* This film became the 17th film to pass $1 billion at the worldwide box office.<ref>[https://twitter.com/boxofficemojo/status/335432187233046528 Twitter - Box Office Mojo]</ref> With a worldwide total box office gross of about $1.2 billion, this film became the second-highest-grossing film of 2013, and at its peak the 6th-highest-grossing film of all time.{{cite|ref=true|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2013&p=.htm|title= 2013 Yearly Box Office Results|work= Box Office Mojo|accessdate= April 3, 2018}}{{cite|ref=true|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|title= All Time Worldwide Box Office Grosses|accessdate= April 3, 2018|work= Box Office Mojo|archiveurl= https://archive.is/26vdh|archivedate= March 28, 2015}}
| Trivia                  = * Director Shane Black previously directed Robert Downey Jr. for the 2005 noir comedy ''{{WP|Kiss Kiss Bang Bang}}''.
* Early into the development, {{WP|Nikolaj Coster-Waldau}} was considered for the role of [[Aldrich Killian (Earth-199999)|Aldich Killian]].{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.artstation.com/artwork/GXgGB4|title=Iron Man 3 (2011) - Extremis Endoarmor Concepts|work=first=Phil|last=Saunders|date=24 April 2019|accessdate=24 April 2019}}
* {{WP|Emilia Clarke}} of ''{{WP|Game of Thrones}}'' fame was originally cast in the movie. Her role was dropped seemingly due to script changes.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://comicbook.com/marvel/2019/05/25/game-of-thrones-star-emilia-clarke-originally-cast-iron-man-3/|title=Game of Thrones Star Emilia Clarke Was Originally Cast in Iron Man 3|work=ComicBook.com|first=JK|last=Schmidt|date=24 May 2019|accessdate=24 May 2019}}
* According to himself, Stan Lee was originally going to have a more prominent appearance.<ref>[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hf7FLHyUAic Iron Man 3 Cameo - Stan's Rants - YouTube]</ref> In a deleted scene from the ''Marvel Cinematic Universe: Phase Two Collection'', it can be seen that Stan Lee's cameo would've had him holding a sign rating a beauty pageant contestant before he even had to, with one of the fellow juries telling him to put it down. Lee would also have been one of the victims of the tear gas Tony Stark would've used to clear the place to use the communications satellite.
* [[Maya Hansen (Earth-199999)|Maya Hansen]] was originally supposed to be the main villain of the film. After the script was finished, Black and co-writer {{WP|Drew Pierce}} received a memo from corporates barring the decision out of concerns for the marketability of a female villain. Hansen's role in the film was reduced and Aldrich Killian was used as the main villain instead. Shane's idea to have a female villain pulling the strings behind a male villain took inspiration from the TV series ''{{WP|Remington Steele}}''.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/shane-black-the-nice-guys-iron-man-3/|title=Shane Black On 'The Nice Guys,' Mel Gibson, And Why A Female 'Iron Man 3' Villain's Gender Changed|last=Ryan|first=Mike|work=Uproxx|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20240825152618/https://uproxx.com/movies/shane-black-the-nice-guys-iron-man-3/|archivedate=August 25, 2023}}
* A [[Hulkbuster Armor]] was originally going to appear as part of the [[Iron Legion (Earth-199999)|Iron Legion]], but it was eliminated to save the suit for a more featured role.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/CEhJQmXjK9e/|title=Phil Saunders on Instagram: "This #hulkbuster was originally done for..."|work=Instagram|first=Phil|last=Saunders|date=30 August 2020|accessdate=3 September 2020}}
* Pearce and Black originally wanted to have Happy Hogan watching {{WP|Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC}} in the hospital as a nod to the Jon Favreau's role in the sitcom ''{{WP|Friends}}''. The idea of using ''{{WP|Downton Abbey}}'' came from Favreau himself.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=47981|title=Shane Black, Drew Pearce Look Back at Billion-Dollar "Iron Man 3"|work=Comic Book Resources|first=Albert|last=Ching|date=19 September 2013|accessdate=24 April 2019}} According to him, the scene of the series shown at Happy Hogan's hospital room was carefully chosen.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://twitter.com/jon_favreau/status/328581485173043201|title=Jon Favreau on Twitter: "Pay attention to what #DowntonAbbey scene Happy is watching in #Ironman3. It was carefully selected"|work=Twitter|first=Jon|last=Favreau|date=28 April 2013|accessdate=4 March 2017}} Said scene features characters Tom Barrow and Sybil Crawley, a chauffeur and the woman of high society he longs for, which could symbolize that Happy secretly harbors feelings for Pepper. In the comics, Happy and Pepper had a romance and were even married.

